  "body": "When replacing an existing pod, the `kubectl replace --force` command fails as it tries to create a pod with a name that is still used by terminating pod.\n\nHow does the `--force` option works?\n1. `kubectl replace` deletes a pod (e.g. mypod)\n2. `kubectl replace` creates a new pod with the same name (mypod)\n\nWhat happens? As the command tries to recreate the pod, it fails as the `mypod` is in `Terminating` state. Thus it can not be created.\n\nThe problem is the `kubectl replace` does not wait for a pod to be deleted.\n\n**Reproducer**:\n1. kubectl run mypod --image=yapei/hello-openshift  --generator=run-pod/v1\n2. kubectl get pod mypod -o yaml > mypod.json\n3. kubectl replace -f  mypod.json --force\n\nThe last command ends with:\n\n```\npod \"mypod\" deleted\nError from server: pods \"mypod\" already exists\n```\n",
